    <h1 style="font-size:22px;font-weight:700;margin:0 0 20px 0;line-height:1.3;">We just shipped the OOS Operating Plan.</h1>

    <p style="margin:0 0 16px 0;font-size:16px;">Jeff is a coach I respect. He spent an hour or so on the phone with me last week talking about OTP, and somewhere in that conversation he said <strong>agents need KPIs like humans do</strong>. That sentence is the start of what we just shipped.</p>

    <p style="margin:0 0 16px 0;font-size:16px;"><strong>The OOS Operating Plan is now live in OTP.</strong> It is the strategy layer above your OOS file: eight sections covering everything from Core Foundation to the 90-Day Execution Engine. You add execution items, the system recommends owners (humans, agents, or hybrid pairs), and you push selected items into your OOS as structured claims when you are ready.</p>

    <p style="margin:0 0 24px 0;font-size:16px;">The point: humans read the plan as plan. Agents query it as queryable rules. Same artifact, both sides reading from it.</p>

    <ul style="margin:0 0 24px 0;padding-left:22px;font-size:16px;">
      <li style="margin-bottom:8px;"><a href="https://orgtp.com/dashboard/oos-operating-plan" style="color:#0f766e;text-decoration:none;font-weight:600;">Open your Operating Plan</a> -- create one in two clicks if you have not yet</li>
      <li style="margin-bottom:8px;"><a href="https://orgtp.com/protocol" style="color:#0f766e;text-decoration:none;font-weight:600;">Read the protocol page</a> -- the longer "why this exists" version</li>
    </ul>

    <p style="margin:0 0 16px 0;font-size:16px;">One conversation, one shipped feature, one concrete answer to <em>"agents need KPIs like humans"</em>: this is the start of that.</p>

    <p style="margin:0 0 8px 0;font-size:16px;">-- David Steel, founder</p>
    <p style="margin:0 0 32px 0;font-size:14px;color:#666;font-style:italic;">PS: thanks Jeff.</p>

